      <h3 id="chapter5Positions">Five DBT positions</h3>

      <p>
        The draft proposes five positions, each with a "supporting direction"
        of non-binding recommendations:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Build on recognised security standards.</strong> A baseline of OIDC FAPI, OAuth 2.0, ISO/IEC 27001/2, NIST CSF, NCSC CAF — or a demonstrably equivalent approach.</li>
        <li><strong>Security assurance should be continuous, not point-in-time.</strong> Ongoing conformance testing, monitoring, and periodic reassessment rather than one-off accreditation.</li>
        <li><strong>Trust should be dynamic.</strong> Machine- and human-readable trust signals — suspension status, risk scoring, incident notifications, credential validity.</li>
        <li><strong>Schemes should support rapid, proportionate incident response.</strong> Suspend/restrict participants, revoke credentials, share threat intelligence, cover emerging threats (synthetic identity, deepfakes, AI-assisted fraud).</li>
        <li><strong>Users should experience clear, consistent support during incidents.</strong> Clarity on what happened, what's being done, and where to get help.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        The chapter also proposes a seven-step process (define the risk
        landscape → identify trust/assurance requirements → minimum security
        controls → fraud management framework → incident management → test
        interoperability → monitor and improve) and eight non-prescriptive
        model clauses (security-by-design, security assurance, fraud
        management, incident response, digital verification, information
        sharing, operational resilience, participant reliance).
      </p>

      <h3 id="chapter5PdtfRelevance">Relevance to PDTF</h3>

      <p>
        PDTF is a data standard, not a scheme operator — its obligation under
        Chapter 5 is representational: does the vocabulary have the terms to
        <em>encode</em> accreditation status, credential validity, risk
        scores, incident notifications, data provenance, and consent scope,
        whatever security posture a given scheme implements. This maps onto
        the Access Control &amp; Sensitivity layer (DPV, ODRL) already
        planned for the ontology, and to the existing
        <a href="/governance/data-security">Data security framework</a>,
        which covers the equivalent ground for PDTF's own trust model
        (KYC/KYB, DID key management, signature verification, revocation,
        audit logging).
      </p>

